<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-566-118  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 566 118.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 28 1989 v23 n35 p10(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Big chill felt through DEC grapevine. (internal cost-cutting memo)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Johnson, Maryfran.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An internal DEC cost-cutting memo has instructed administrators inpersonnel, purchasing, finance, and other support departments tocut the 1990 operating budget by 10 percent and to plan forreductions of up to 25 percent by 1991.andP;  Glimpses of the memo in aBoston newspaper article caused anxiety in the minicomputermarketplace, which is already reeling from negative forecasts forPrime Computer Inc, Wang Laboratories Inc, and Data General Corp.andO;DEC officials deny that any layoffs will take place, but analystsexpect cutbacks and possibly the loss of up to 7,000 jobs.andP;  Thecompany is restructuring many of its operations, transferringemployees from manufacturing jobs in to sales and servicepositions and working to reduce its overhead.andP;  Industry observersnote that DEC could cut costs without layoffs by cutting back onconsulting services, travel budgets, and other expenses.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Digital Equipment Corp. (costs).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     Computer industryOrganization StructureCost Reduction.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>